1.

The bottm Suggested spelling: bottom of a pan is made of a 4-mm-thick aluminum layer. In order to increase the rate of heat transfer through the bottom of the pan, someone proposes a design for the bottom tht Suggested spelling: that consists of a 3-mm-thick copper layer sandwiched between two 2-mm-thick aluminum layers. Will the new design conduct heat better?º

 

Yes
→No
No, the new design introduces the thermal resistance of the copper layer in addition to the thermal resistance of the aluminum which has the same value for both designs. Therefore, the new design will be a poorer conductor of heat.

6.Consider a window glass consisting of two 4-mm thick glass sheets pressed tightly against each other. Compare the heat transfer rate through this window with that of one consisting of a single 8-mm-thick glass sheet under identical conditions. The heat transfer rate in window glass consisting of two 4-mm thick glass sheets will be higher relative to the one which consists of a single 8 mm thick glass sheet.
Yes
→No
No, the window glass which consists of two 4 mm thick glass sheets pressed tightly against each other will probably have thermal contact resistance which serves as an additional thermal resistance to heat transfer through window, and thus the heat transfer rate will be smaller relative to the one which consists of a single 8 mm thick glass sheet.

18.

An air-standard Stirling cycle operates with a maximum pressure of 600 psia and a minimum pressure of 10 psia. The maximum volume of the air is 10 times the minimum volume. The temperature during the heat rejection process is 100°F. Calculate the specific heat added to and rejected by this cycle, as well as the net specific work produced by the cycle. Use constant specific heats at room temperature.

The properties of air at room temperature are R = 0.3704 psia⋅ft3/lbm⋅R = 0.06855 Btu/lbm⋅R, cp = 0.240 Btu/lbm⋅R, cv = 0.171 Btu/lbm⋅R, and k = l.4

 

The specific heat added to this cycle is Btu/lbm.

 

The heat rejected by this cycle  Btu/ lbm.

 

The net specific work produced by the cycle Btu/ lbm.


 
Explanation:

The assumption made here is that air is an ideal gas with constant specific heats.

 

 

Applying the ideal gas equation to the isothermal process 3-4 gives 

 

P4=P3V3V4P4=P3V3V4

 

P4=(10 psia)(10)P4=10 psia10

 

P4=100 psiaP4=100 psia

 

Since process 4-1 is a constant volume process,

 

T1=T4(P1P2)T1=T4P1P2

 

T1=(560 R)(600 psia100 psia)T1=560 R600 psia100 psia

 

T1=3360 RT1=3360 R

 

According to the first law and work integral,

 

qin=w1-2=RT1ln(V2V1)qin=w1-2=RT1lnV2V1

 

qin=(0.06855 Btu/lbm⋅R)(3360 R)ln(10)qin=0.06855 Btu/lbm·R3360 Rln10

 

qin=530.3498 Btu/Ibmqin=530.3498 Btu/Ibm

 

and

 

qout=w3-4=RT3ln(V4V3)qout=w3-4=RT3lnV4V3

 

qout=(0.06855 Btu/lbm⋅R)(560 R)ln(110)qout=0.06855 Btu/lbm·R560 Rln110

 

The net work is then

 

wnet=qin−qoutwnet=qin-qout

 

wnet=(530.3498-3360) Btu/Ibmwnet=530.3498-3360 Btu/Ibm

 

wnet=88.3916 Btu/Ibmwnet=88.3916 Btu/Ibm

19.

An air-standard Stirling cycle operates with a maximum pressure of 600 psia and a minimum pressure of 10 psia. The maximum volume of the air is 10 times the minimum volume. The temperature during the heat rejection process is 98°F. How much heat is stored (and recovered) in the regenerator? Use constant specific heats at room temperature.

 

The properties of air at room temperature are R = 0.3704 psia-ft3/lbm·R, cp = 0.240 Btu/lbm·R, cv = 0.171 Btu/lbm·R, and k = l.4.

, we ignore the steel bars between the plates in heat transfer analysis.

Each bar has a thermal conductivity of 12 W/m⋅K, a specific heat of 500 J/kg⋅K, and a density of 7.9 g/cm3. The bars are situated in between the two plates, and they are occasionally submerged in hot liquid at 300°C with a convection heat transfer coefficient of 96 W/m2⋅K. The length of each bar that is exposed to the hot liquid is 25 mm with an initial temperature of 15°C. The maximum use temperature allowed for ASTM A479 904L bars is 260°C (ASME Code for Process Piping, ASME B31.3-2014, Table A-1M). If the bars are submerged in the hot liquid for 5 min, will they be in compliance with the ASME code? How long will it take for the bars to reach the maximum use temperature?

 

, the stainless steel (ASTM A479 904L) bars be in compliance with the ASME code for Process Piping.

 

The time taken for the bars to reach the maximum use temperature is s.

 

 

 

 

 


 
Explanation:

Following assumptions have been made here.

 

1. Heat conduction in the bar is one-dimensional since it is long and it has thermal symmetry about the centerline.

2 The thermal properties of the shaft and the heat transfer coefficient are constant. 

 

The characteristic length of the bar is

 

Lc=VAs=L×B24×(L×B)=B4=0.0124=0.003Lc=VAs=L×B24×L×B=B4=0.0124=0.003

T(t)−T∞Ti−T∞=e−btTt-T∞Ti-T∞=e-bt

, The ASTM A437 B4B bolts be in compliance with the ASME code for Process Piping.

 

The taken by the bolts to reach the minimum suitable temperature is min.

 


 
Explanation:
